properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system will produce strong winds and blowing snow beginning Thursday afternoon. Near-blizzard conditions are likely Thursday night with winds gusts up to 80 km/h. Blizzard conditions are likely for Friday with fresh snow moving into the area and strong easterly winds forecast. Blizzard conditions should improve by Saturday morning as the low weakens. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Cold conditions are possible with severe wind chill values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2020-03-26T11:28:40-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall tonight into Thursday. Snow, heavy at times, will begin late this evening and end early Thursday afternoon. The heaviest snow is likely early Thursday morning with total snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm possible. Travel may become difficult due to quickly accumulating snow. Motorists are advised to allow extra time to reach their destination. There is still some uncertainty with the track of the low pressure system responsible for this snow. Environment Canada meteorologists will continue to monitor this situation closely. A snowfall warning may be required. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and rain expected Thursday night and Friday. Maximum snowfall: near 15 cm possible for parts of southern, central and northern Newfoundland. Maximum rainfall: 30 to 50 mm possible, most likely somewhere along the south coast. Strongest winds: southeasterly 80 to 100 km/h followed by southwesterlies near 80 km/h. Time span: Thursday night, Friday, Friday night and likely Saturday for the west and north. Remarks: A low pressure system will approach Newfoundland from the south on Thursday and track through western or central regions of the Island. Snow will begin Thursday evening in the south and spread elsewhere throughout the night. Precipitation will likely change over to rain for southern areas overnight Thursday night and elsewhere on Friday. Precipitation may change back to snow along the west coast and over the Great Northern Peninsula on Friday night while elsewhere conditions will taper off. Snow will eventually taper off to flurries in the west and north by Saturday afternoon or evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2020-03-26T17:22:47-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-03-26T01:23:47-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2795904735.2020

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A snowstorm is expected Friday and Saturday. Maximum snowfall: 15 to 30 cm possible in the southeast, central and along the mid coast. Maximum rainfall: 10 to 15 mm possible over southeastern Labrador and the straits. Strongest winds: northerly near 80 km/h. Time span: Friday morning to Saturday evening. Remarks: A low pressure system will approach Labrador from the south on Friday and track through eastern regions on Saturday. Snow will begin Friday morning along the Strait and spread elsewhere throughout the day. Precipitation will likely change over to rain for southeastern areas on Friday night while elsewhere remains snow throughout the event. Strong northerly winds will develop behind the system on Friday night and persist over most areas on Saturday. Wind will combine with fresh snow to cause significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Conditions should improve by Saturday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2020-03-26T17:32:08-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Mixed precipitation expected for Thursday into Friday. Total snowfall: 5 to 20 cm. 30 cm or more possible over the Cape Breton Highlands. Freezing rain: 2 to 5 mm possible. Maximum wind gusts: northeasterly up to 70 km/h. Les Suetes winds up to 80 km/h. Locations: central and eastern Nova Scotia, including Cape Breton. Time span: Thursday afternoon until Friday afternoon. Remarks: Precipitation is expected to begin as heavy wet snow Thursday morning then transition to a mix of ice pellets or freezing rain in the evening and overnight. Freezing rain may create hazardous conditions over Cape Breton Thursday night into Friday morning. On Friday the area of precipitation will have moved out of the province, however strong northwesterly winds in flurries will likely persist in onshore winds from the Gulf of Saint Lawrence giving reduced visibilities in snow and blowing snow. The highest total snowfall accumulations are expected over the Cape Breton Highlands. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
